numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>661</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00WZ</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WZ.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Query modes and polarities">Query modes and polarities</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Given an address <fr:code>x</fr:code> and a relation symbol <fr:code>r</fr:code>, there are several useful queries that we might wish to make:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>We might wish to find all <fr:em>incoming</fr:em> edges to <fr:code>x</fr:code> in <fr:code>r</fr:code>, or we may wish to find all <fr:em>outgoing</fr:em> edges from <fr:code>x</fr:code> in <fr:code>r</fr:code>. We shall refer to the differenec between incoming and outgoing edges is referred to as a <fr:em>polarity</fr:em>.</fr:li>
    <fr:li>Rather than searching for edges, we may wish to search for <fr:em>paths</fr:em> — which corresponds to passing from a relation to its preorder reflection. We will refer to this distinction as a <fr:em>mode</fr:em>.</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-005P.xml"
addr="jms-005P"
title="Forester">Forester</fr:link> supports both polarities and modes for relational queries via the following built-in constants:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\query/incoming]]></fr:code> and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/outgoing]]></fr:code> denote the two polarities.</fr:li>
    <fr:li><fr:code><![CDATA[\query/edges]]></fr:code> and <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/paths]]></fr:code> represent the two modes.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>663</fr:anchor><fr:addr
type="user">jms-00WY</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00WY.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="The syntax of a relational query">The syntax of a relational query</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WW</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A relational query takes the following form:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/rel{mode}{polarity}{relation}{addr}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>In the above, <fr:code>mode</fr:code> and <fr:code>polarity</fr:code> must evaluate to mode and polarity constants as in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00WZ"
href="jms-00WZ.xml" />; <fr:code>relation</fr:code> must evaluate to a relation symbol as in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00WX"
href="jms-00WX.xml" />.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
